&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p data-sider-select-id=&quot;28f1473e-57fd-4b72-8311-8a34538164b4&quot;&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong data-sider-select-id=&quot;bae3355e-9ec4-4b0d-89ff-2f645cc0d436&quot;&gt;Total Mechanical Energy&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-sider-select-id=&quot;2b5cbb66-a876-48d8-90e0-c19887b147c2&quot;&gt;The sum of the kinetic and potential energy of an object is known as the&lt;strong data-sider-select-id=&quot;feeb5d45-e371-48f4-8c60-2c350a045c93&quot;&gt; Total Mechanical Energy.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-sider-select-id=&quot;bdf97a3d-ce8c-4307-8c4b-85de75e009e9&quot;&gt;&lt;strong data-sider-select-id=&quot;806772ff-7e2d-44a2-b08a-946a6add076d&quot;&gt;Kinetic Energy&lt;/strong&gt; is the energy that an &lt;strong data-sider-select-id=&quot;3b02a7a8-3b74-4f34-aed3-27ab13cde053&quot;&gt;object possesses due to its motion&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-sider-select-id=&quot;8798d292-b838-4207-9362-df5418786061&quot;&gt;&lt;strong data-sider-select-id=&quot;330196be-43df-432c-be5e-911465ac1b1e&quot;&gt;Potential Energy&lt;/strong&gt; is the energy stored in an object due to its&lt;strong data-sider-select-id=&quot;faac87e5-fe14-4b57-b170-144a792d8bdc&quot;&gt; position or configuration&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The principle of conservation of mechanical energy states that if only conservative forces are acting, the total mechanical energy of a system remains constant.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table style=&quot;width: 350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;th&gt;Option&lt;/th&gt;
			&lt;th&gt;Details&lt;/th&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Total Mechanical Energy&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;This is the correct answer. It represents the sum of an object&amp;#39;s kinetic and potential energy.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Total Frictional Energy&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Frictional energy refers to the energy lost due to friction. It is not related to the sum of kinetic and potential energy.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Total Heat Energy&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Heat energy is the result of the movement of tiny particles called atoms, molecules or ions in solids, liquids, and gases. It is not the sum of kinetic and potential energy.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Total Potential Energy&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Potential energy is just one part of the total mechanical energy, not the sum of kinetic and potential energy.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The primary function of the stem in plants is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;conducting water and nutrients from the roots to the leaves.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The stem plays a crucial role in the vascular system of plants, serving multiple functions that support the plant&amp;#39;s overall physiology and structural integrity. Among the options provided:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1) Absorption of water from the soil:&lt;/strong&gt; This function is primarily attributed to the roots, not the stem. Roots are responsible for penetrating the soil to absorb water and dissolved minerals, which are then transported to other parts of the plant.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2) Anchoring the plant in the ground:&lt;/strong&gt; While the stem does provide structural support, the primary function of anchoring the plant firmly in the soil falls to the roots. The root system spreads out to firmly secure the plant and support the stem&amp;#39;s upright position.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3) Conducting water and nutrients from the roots to the leaves:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a primary function of the stem. The stem houses the plant&amp;rsquo;s vascular system, which includes the xylem and phloem. The xylem conducts water and dissolved minerals collected by the roots to the leaves and other parts of the plant. Simultaneously, the phloem transports the sugars and other organic nutrients produced by photosynthesis in the leaves to different parts of the plant. This communication highway helps maintain the plant&amp;rsquo;s metabolism and growth.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4) Producing food through photosynthesis:&lt;/strong&gt; While some stems can engage in photosynthesis (especially in plants with modified stems or in young, green stems), the primary site of photosynthesis is the leaves, not the stem. Leaves are uniquely structured with chloroplasts to efficiently capture light energy and convert it into chemical energy (sugars).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conclusion:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Therefore, Option 3 accurately describes the stem&amp;#39;s primary function in conducting water and nutrients from the roots to the leaves.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Work&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Work &lt;/strong&gt;is the &lt;strong&gt;product &lt;/strong&gt;of the &lt;strong&gt;component &lt;/strong&gt;of the &lt;strong&gt;force &lt;/strong&gt;in the &lt;strong&gt;direction &lt;/strong&gt;of the &lt;strong&gt;displacement &lt;/strong&gt;and the &lt;strong&gt;magnitude &lt;/strong&gt;of this &lt;strong&gt;displacement&lt;/strong&gt;.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For work to be done, in a scientific sense, a &lt;strong&gt;force &lt;/strong&gt;must be &lt;strong&gt;exerted &lt;/strong&gt;and there must be &lt;strong&gt;displacement &lt;/strong&gt;in the &lt;strong&gt;direction &lt;/strong&gt;of the &lt;strong&gt;force&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mathematically &lt;/strong&gt;it is represented&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; SI unit&lt;/strong&gt; of work is the &lt;strong&gt;joule &lt;/strong&gt;(J), which is defined as the work done by a force of 1 Newton in moving an object through a distance of 1 meter in the direction of the force.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Momentum &lt;/strong&gt;is a &lt;strong&gt;measurement &lt;/strong&gt;of &lt;strong&gt;mass &lt;/strong&gt;in &lt;strong&gt;motion &lt;/strong&gt;i.e.&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;how much mass &lt;/strong&gt;is in &lt;strong&gt;how much motion&lt;/strong&gt;.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Momentum &lt;/strong&gt;= &lt;strong&gt;Mass x Velocity.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impulse &lt;/strong&gt;is a term that &lt;strong&gt;quantifies &lt;/strong&gt;the &lt;strong&gt;overall effect &lt;/strong&gt;of a &lt;strong&gt;force acting&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;over time&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is conventionally given the &lt;strong&gt;symbol J &lt;/strong&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;expressed &lt;/strong&gt;in &lt;strong&gt;Newton&lt;/strong&gt;-&lt;strong&gt;seconds&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Power is the rate at which work is done.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; SI unit&lt;/strong&gt; of power is &lt;strong&gt;Watt &lt;/strong&gt;(W)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Power &lt;/strong&gt;= &lt;strong&gt;Work / time&lt;span style=&quot;display: none;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mahadev Lal Saraf&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Salt Satyagraha in Bhagalpur was led by &lt;strong&gt;Mahadev Lal Saraf&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mahadev Lal Saraf&lt;/strong&gt; of &lt;strong&gt;Bhagalpur &lt;/strong&gt;was one of the important freedom fighters.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He organized the &lt;strong&gt;Salt Satyagraha in Bhagalpur&lt;/strong&gt; in the year 1930. He was highly influenced by Gandhiji&amp;#39;s thoughts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this movement Use of Khadi, the refusal to pay Chaukigari, a message against intoxicating drinks was the most important point.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On dated &lt;strong&gt;31&lt;sup&gt;st&lt;/sup&gt; march to 3&lt;sup&gt;rd&lt;/sup&gt; April 1930&lt;/strong&gt; Pt. Jawaharlal visited Bihar for the success of the Satyagraha.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Swadeshi Committee&lt;/strong&gt; was set up at Patna.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;centrifugation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;The working principle of a washing machine is &lt;strong&gt;centrifugation.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Centrifugation is a&lt;strong&gt; separation process that uses the action of centrifugal force &lt;/strong&gt;to promote accelerated settling of particles in a &lt;strong&gt;solid-liquid mixture.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Centrifugation.&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Centrifugation-&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Centrifugation is a technique &lt;strong&gt;used for the separation of particles from a solution &lt;/strong&gt;according to their size, shape, density, viscosity of the medium and rotor speed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The particles are &lt;strong&gt;suspended in a liquid medium and placed in a centrifuge tube.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The tube is then placed in a &lt;strong&gt;rotor and spun&lt;/strong&gt; at a defined &lt;strong&gt;speed.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Zero&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The order of reaction&amp;nbsp;represents the number of reactants whose concentration directly affects the rate of reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In zero Order Reactions, the rate of reaction is independent of the concentration of the reactants.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the first-order reaction, the rate of reaction depends on the concentration of only one of the reactants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In second-order&amp;nbsp;reactions, the rate of&amp;nbsp;reactions can be obtained either from the concentration of one reactant squared or from the concentration of two separate reactants.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The rate law or rate equation for a chemical reaction is an equation that links the initial or forward reaction rate with the concentrations or pressures of the reactants and constant parameters (normally rate coefficients and partial reaction orders).&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; option 2)&lt;/strong&gt; i.e.&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Stupa.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;three forms&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of Buddhist architecture.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); width: 300px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Name&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Details&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Stupa&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;The dome-like structure where relics of Buddha are preserved.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Chaitya&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;It is a temple or shrine with a prayer hall.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Vihara&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;It is a monastery.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;None of the above.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; &quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Estimates Committee is a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Lok Sabha committee.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On 3&lt;span style=&quot;line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;rd&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;April 1950, the Provisional Parliament adopted the motion to elect the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;First Estimates Committee and on 10&lt;span style=&quot;line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em; font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;th&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;April 1950, the Committee was elected.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Committee consists of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;no more than 30 members from Lok Sabha&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;who are elected by the House each year from among its members by means of a single transferable vote according to the principle of proportional&amp;nbsp;representation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The Speaker&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;has the right to nominate the committee chair from among its members.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The Committee continues to review the estimates from time to time&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;during the financial year and can report to the House as it progresses with its investigation or upon the completion of the examination.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; &quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Public Accounts Committee consists of a total of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;22 members&lt;/span&gt;.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Out of these&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;22 members, 15 are from Lok Sabha and 7 from Rajya Sabha&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The term of office of PAC is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;one year&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Members are elected by&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;parliament every year with a proportional representation system&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The chairperson of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Public Accounts Committee&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is appointed by the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Lok Sabha speaker&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;chairperson&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Public Accounts Committee&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is always from the main opposition party.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Function&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;- To examines the annual audit reports of the Comptroller and Auditor General of India (CAG), which are laid before the Parliament by the President.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(77, 81, 86);&quot;&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Committee on Public Undertakings&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a committee of selected members of parliament,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;constituted by the Parliament of India.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(77, 81, 86);&quot;&gt;The purpose of examining the reports and accounts of the public sector undertakings as specified in the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;fourth schedule&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the Rules of Procedure and Conduct of Business in Lok Sabha.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(32, 33, 36);&quot;&gt;The committee consists of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;twenty-two members, fifteen elected by Lok Sabha,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;the lower house of the Parliament, and not more than&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;seven&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;members of Rajya Sabha&lt;/span&gt;, the upper house of the Parliament.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;on the live wire&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Fuse is an electrical safety device&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;used to protect an electrical or electronic device from overcurrents.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The electric fuse is connected&amp;nbsp;to the &lt;strong&gt;live wire&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the current above the rated value of the fuse flows through the fuse, the heat generated will cause the fuse wire to melt, thereby breaking the connection.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;An electric fuse&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a protective device that protects electrical equipment in the circuit by breaking the circuit when there is a short circuit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It contains a fuse wire which has a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;low melting point&lt;/span&gt;, it allows normal current to pass through it safely but if there is any short circuit fuse wire can&amp;rsquo;t withstand the heat produced by that current (infinite current) so it melts and breaks the circuit&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hence fuse wire used to have a&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;low melting point and high resistance&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to avoid overload or short circuit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Whereas the fuse rating of electrical fuse is the maximum amount of current can pass through it without melting the fuse wire.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The material used for&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;fuse&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;elements must be of:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Low melting point, low ohmic loss.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;High resistivity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Low cost and free from detraction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The material used for making fuse element has a low melting point such as tin, lead, or zinc.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A low melting point is, however, available with a high specific resistance metal.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The material mainly used for fuse elements are tin, lead, silver, copper, zinc, aluminium,&amp;nbsp; and an alloy of lead and tin.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;They all lack back bone.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The common characteristic among Amoeba, Starfish, Ant, and Spider is that they all lack a backbone or vertebral column.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are all invertebrates, which means they do not possess a rigid internal skeleton made of bones. Instead, they have different structures or adaptations to support their bodies and perform various functions.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Amoeba is a unicellular organism, and as such, it does not have any skeletal structure. It maintains its shape through its flexible cell membrane and cytoplasm.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Starfish, Ants, and Spiders are all multicellular organisms, but they belong to different phyla and exhibit different body structures. However, they share the common characteristic of lacking a backbone.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Starfish belong to the phylum Echinodermata and have a hard exoskeleton composed of calcium carbonate plates called ossicles. They do not have a true backbone.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ants belong to the phylum Arthropoda and have a segmented body supported by an exoskeleton made of chitin. They do not possess a backbone.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
